##Face masks from neighboring countries and unilateral border closures: When the "Bulk" EU meets a new crisis

Multilateral Consultation and exchange, once the EU's biggest brand in a world of contradictions, has disappeared in the face of Catastrophe.

”

On the one hand, a foreign aid plane carrying 31 tons of medical supplies and personnel landed at the Leonardo Da Vinci–Fiumicino Airport in Italy, on the other hand, Germany, a member of the European Union, has ordered 830,000 masks from overseas to be withheld because of a ban on medical supplies.

This is the new crown disease of the impact of the situation in Italy is a true portrayal. The health care system in the hard hit areas of the north is on the verge of collapse, and Prime Minister Contes has announced the closure of the border and the closure of all shops in the country, including pharmacies and supermarkets. The European Union, the "Central Government" , and its member states have so far done little to help Italy.

This is not the first time Italians have felt abandoned by the EU. Back in the Libyan crisis, black ships on the Mediterranean and volunteers from Germany and northern Europe sent large numbers of refugees to Italy. Italy did not receive the EU's $6 BILLION REFUGEE FUND, as Turkey did, after then Deputy Prime Minister Salvini closed all ports to refugee ships last summer, italy has again become the object of fierce criticism from the EU.

Italy's experience is a footnote in the "bulk" of the EU.

From the European debt crisis in 2010 to the refugee crisis in 2015 to Britain's Brexit in 2016, the quasi federal state of the European Union has been challenged three times in just a decade by a sharp decline in cohesion or even the dissolution of the Union, and now the new coronavirus may be another crisis for the European Union.

Will it be as united as it was during the euro crisis, or as divided as it was during the refugee crisis?

So far, it seems that the EU countries have chosen the latter.

In addition to withholding scarce medical supplies, as Germany did, Austria and Slovenia, Italy's neighbors, were also among the first to respond to the situation without informing Italy in a timely manner, to declare a unilateral border blockade against Italy.

"This is by no means a symbol of European unity! " Said Maurizio Massari, Italy's ambassador to Europe. No country responded to Italy's request for medical aid to EU member states.

According to Daily Mirror, citing sources in Brussels, the key to such difficult EU level negotiations on pooling medical supplies remains the Germans fighting over the masks.

"unilateral action can only trigger domino effect within the EU and affect the timely delivery of medical supplies to patients and hospitals, " even the German President of the European Commission, Joachim von Der Leyen, said without naming his country.

In an EU statement, the commission also formally warned that member states could face legal consequences if they deliberately restrict the transport of medical supplies or medicines.

The German government announced a policy change on Wednesday to relax its ban on medical exports and allow transit for EU partners, after public criticism and criticism. In particular, the German Ministry of Economy emphasizes the protection of the security of the German people and the maintenance of European solidarity in special times as its primary objectives.

Germany imposed a ban on the export of medical supplies on March 4, after seizing 240,000 masks bought by Switzerland and a shipment from Austria. Spann, Germany's health minister, who was under fire from his European counterparts at the time, kicked the ball straight to the EU: "As long as the EU does not impose an all-european export ban, our ban is justified. "

But Germany is not the only EU country to be "self-serving" . France had previously announced that it would take possession of all its stockpiles of masks, and the Czech Republic had also announced that it would immediately follow up and impose a ban on the export of medical supplies.

All European countries know that if they can not quickly contain the outbreak, they could be Italy today in a week's time, so hoarding as many masks as possible is a last resort. "We have the same problem as Italy, " Force, Marche, the Czech Health Minister, told the Council of Ministers of Bosnia and Herzegovina. "The demand for medical supplies is far greater than the supply. If we had the resources, we might have supported Italy,"he said, referring to the Czech Republic, which had only 12 confirmed cases, more than 4,000 cases have been confirmed in Italy. The number of confirmed cases in the Czech Republic now stands at 344.

As for the problem of the blockade of the border, which Austria and Slovenia have taken the lead in turning against Italy, in contrast to the current flow of vehicles waiting to pass through the Brenner Pass, which stretches for several kilometres every day, the Council of Ministers of Bosnia and Herzegovina in Brussels on March 6th.

Although the meeting lasted four hours, nearly double the length of previous ministerial meetings, no concrete measures were agreed. The only consensus was a declaration that it would ensure the movement of people in the EU's internal market, with no clear border closures. "[ the other consensus ] is that solidarity with Italy is not just rhetorical, " declared Rudolf Anschober, Austria's health minister

Ironically, with the dramatic deterioration of the European epidemic over the past week, the European Union's announcement on March 16th of an across-the-board border blockade, and countries'inaction on Italy, the only consensus reached at the March 4th meeting collapsed.

European Commission President jean-claude von Der Leyen spoke out against unilateral border closures on March 13th and expressed concern about the impact on people living in border areas. Von Der Leyen wants member states to prioritize flexible measures, such as temperature screening points at their borders, rather than blanket closures. Johansen Johansson, the European Commission's Internal Affairs Commissioner, has also demanded that countries notify their neighbours at least in time before sealing their borders.

But in fact, not only do countries'border closures fail to notify their neighbours and EU headquarters in a timely manner, they also fail to notify their neighbours when a state of emergency is in force.

Earlier, on the night of March 14, French Prime Minister Philip of Swabia had announced without warning that France had entered Phase III of the epidemic, closing all non essential shops. For a while, the French of Alsace and Lorraine flocked to Germany to buy goods. Alsace and Lorraine, whose residents speak mostly German, cross the border frequently, but the German state of Bavaria, which borders France, is one of the three most affected.

Multilateral Consultation and exchange, once the EU's biggest brand in a world of contradictions, is now missing in the face of Catastrophe.

One argument is that the EU's transnational function is mainly in areas such as trade and the economy. It is clear from the EU treaty that countries are left to deal with their own health policies, which has led to national fragmentation in dealing with the epidemic.

But even on the EU's most skilful fiscal issues, Brussels has done little to help Rome.

Contes, Italy's prime minister, announced last week that he would spend $25bn to ensure the country's economy does not collapse and to fund businesses and workers that have stopped work. But because of its weak fiscal position, the Italian government is not only unable to deliver the $75bn package that Contes had hoped for, but needs the EU to help it with half of the $25bn it has shrunk.

Although the European Union first announced the relaxation of fiscal discipline on Italy, and the establishment of 25 billion euros European Union funds (EU Corona Fonds) . But that figure pales in comparison to the $460bn of guarantees announced on Friday by Germany's deep pocketed economy ministry.

The bad news for Italy also came from the European Central Bank. On March 12th Lagarde, the president of the European Central Bank, kept the base rate unchanged while implying that it was not the ECB's job to cut interest rates for member states. At one point, that led to a 100 basis point rise in Italian bond yields.

Perhaps aware that the EU is falling apart in the face of the epidemic, von Der Leyen and the president of the European Council, Michelle, will join the 27 EU leaders in Tuesday to urge countries to fully open their borders to the movement of goods, to ensure that countries are supplied with the basic supplies that have already been snapped up from shelves, while making every effort to ensure that medical supplies are distributed among countries according to the severity of the outbreak.

The question is whether Germany, with 7,461 confirmed cases, and France, with 6,633, have the resources to save Italy or even Spain?
